Table 1 shows the comparison of the sensitivity aspects of the previously reported CDs with the TATA-Car CDs [4,20–22,42,55–60]. Thus, the proposed sensor is highly selective for detecting AA in the nanomolar range with excellent sensitivity compared to the above-mentioned CDs-based sensors. We believe that the PL quenching of TATA-Car CDs might have occurred through an electron transfer process. Firstly, PL quenching might have occurred due to the non-radiative photoinduced electron transfer process from photoexcited TATA-Car CDs to the empty d-orbitals of Cu2+ ions. This is possibly due to the strong interaction of imidazole, hydroxyl, and carboxyl moieties from the TATA-Car CDs with Cu2+ ions. Furthermore, the PL quenching of TATA-Car CDs by Cu2+ ions occurred because of the maximum thermodynamic affinity of Cu2+ ions and sufficient chelating efficiency with carboxyl groups [61]. On the other hand, after treatment with AA, the recovery of the fluorescence of TATA-Car CDs-Cu2+ occurred by proceeding with the reduction of Cu2+ ions and eventually making fluorescence turn-on behavior possible ( Scheme 2
). Also, from the selectivity results ( Fig. 6D), it is clear that fluorescence recovery has not been delivered by the TATA-Car CDs-Cu2+ except for AA. We believe this fluorescence turn-on behavior was also accompanied by the presence of the electron-rich furan ring in the AA structure. When comparing the fluorescence recovery of the TATA-Car CDs-Cu2+ against AA with other interferants, the latter might not have much electron-donating capability. Further, the selectivity of the TATA-Car CDs-Cu2+ was examined using different oxidizing agents, including KBr, KI, KClO3, KNO3, Na2Cr2O7, and KMnO4, along with AA (
Fig. S4
). No fluorescence enhancement was observed in the TATA-Car CDs-Cu2+ after treatment with the above-mentioned interferents (50 nM), except for AA (15 nM). These results suggest that the proposed sensor has excellent selectivity for AA even in the presence of functionally similar oxidizing agents.
